<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN ULRICH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WAGNER: "Das Rheingold." Marjana Lipovsek, Jadwiga Rappe, James Morris, Theo 
Adam, Heinz Zednik, Andreas Schmidt; Symphonie-Orchester des Bayerischen 
Rundfunks conducted by Bernard Haitink. 
</P>
<P>
EMI-Angel 49853-2 (two compact discs). The order may be jumbled, but the 
priorities are right: with his most recently published installment of the 
"Ring," Haitink capitalizes on the promise of the previously released "Die 
Walkure." What the conducting lacks in sheer, Soltiesque dazzle, it more than 
makes up in its adherence to line and respect for architecture, a symphonist's 
probing view of the score, animated by the Bavarians' accomplished playing and 
EMI's resourceful engineers. Morris' grainy bass epitomizes the callow young 
Wotan. Adam, a distinguished Wotan of yesteryear, brings uncommon intelligence 
and a tight top to Alberich. Noted, too, with pleasure: Lipovsek's steady 
Fricka, Rappe's opulent Erda, Zednik's wily Loge and Schmidt's Donner, a rich, 
baritonal, golden-age performance. ALLAN ULRICH 
</P>
</TEXT>
