<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE $115,000 RACING SHELLS FOR NEWPORT AQUATIC CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article (June 13) on Amateur Athletic Foundation funding in Orange County 
featured a great photo of the junior women's quad boat from the Newport Aquatic 
Center. These girls will be going on to national-level competition later this 
month and, hopefully, also will continue to row at the high school and 
collegiate level. 
</P>
<P>
I would like to point out that the Newport Aquatic Center offers the only 
opportunity for any woman of any age to row in all of Orange County. The two 
collegiate programs in Orange County, at UC Irvine and Orange Coast College, 
both offer men's teams but do not have rowing programs available to women. 
There are no other high school rowing programs in the county. 
</P>
<P>
Although the Newport Aquatic Center is marginally able to keep its doors open 
from month to month on its membership fees, it is only through the generosity 
of organizations such as the AAF and the donations of individuals that programs 
like this one for high school kids can be offered. The article makes reference 
to lessons being offered for $50, while failing to mention that this is the 
cost of a five-lesson series. 
</P>
<P>
It is the purpose of the Newport Aquatic Center to promote the sports of 
kayaking, canoeing and rowing at all levels of ability, and the center is 
wheelchair-accessible. 
</P>
<P>
MARTHA SINGER 
</P>
<P>
Irvine 
</P>
</TEXT>
