<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: IN AGE OF SUPER-BRATS -- TENNIS, ANYONE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1905, May Sutton, the first non-English Wimbledon champion, caused a flap 
when she rolled up her shirt sleeves on the court because she was "too hot." 
The corset and the petticoats she was wearing probably had a lot to do with it. 
</P>
<P>
A few years later, Billie Tapscott played Wimbledon without stockings. Get 
outta here! From there on, the dress code got out of control. Alice Marble wore 
short tennis shorts, Gussie Moran revealed lace-edged panties, and Billie Jean 
King, in her famous match against Bobby Riggs in 1973, wore a mint-green tennis 
dress with sky-blue collar decorated with a band of rhinestones and green 
sequins. 
</P>
<P>
Tennis court apparel was destined to change. Andre Agassi, from Las Vegas, came 
head to head with the French Tennis Federation because he is a forerunner of 
the hot lava Spandex Age. When he appeared on the court recently dressed in 
glowing pink and black shirt, black denim shorts, pink cycling tights 
underneath and matching shoes and headband, the federation screamed "ban" and 
suggested a dress code for tennis players to be adopted by the United States 
and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
When our young son was 8 years old, I entered him in a local tennis tournament 
because it would keep him busy for an hour while I went to the supermarket. The 
fact that he had never played a tennis game in his entire life was irrelevant. 
He drove me nuts at the store. 
</P>
<P>
His court attire was plaid shorts down to his knees, a pair of black high-tops 
and a sweat shirt. His opponent was in white, had a headband and ("We are in 
deep trouble, kid!") a sweatband on his wrist. He probably squeezed a tennis 
ball in his sleep to strengthen his forearm. He had to tell my son where to 
stand to serve and when to change sides. I couldn't watch. 
</P>
<P>
When I returned from the store, my son was sitting on the curb with a new can 
of tennis balls. His opponent told him he had won. 
</P>
<P>
It's hard to get excited over what tennis players choose to wear on court. Good 
tennis is good tennis no matter how you dress it. What we should be getting 
excited about are the lack of manners and the foul language. It is not 
tolerated in any other sports event. Yet these super-brats are allowed to throw 
rackets, challenge decisions with profanities and make obscene gestures to the 
fans. 
</P>
<P>
They can glow in the dark if they want to. Just knock it off with the theatrics 
and play tennis! 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
