<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: CUB SCOUTMASTER LEADS THE PACK IN VOLUNTEER EFFORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELDON ITO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For 10 years before Mark Wright came on the scene, there were no Cub Scouts in 
Beverly Hills. The program was the victim of declining elementary school 
enrollment and a lack of volunteer parents. 
</P>
<P>
So when Wright's son, Darrin, wanted to join the Scouts a few years ago, he had 
nowhere to go. 
</P>
<P>
"Well, some of the other parents and I got together and decided we wanted our 
kids to be in Cub Scouts," said Wright, 42, who was a Cub Scout as a boy in 
Merced. 
</P>
<P>
In 1986, the parents re-established Beverly Hills' Pack 100 and chose Wright to 
be its first Cubmaster. 
</P>
<P>
But the Scouts again ran into the problems of 10 years ago, and during the 
first year the pack was really only a den of six Cubs. Then Wright came up with 
an inspired idea. 
</P>
<P>
"Normally, a Cub pack is usually for one school," said Wright, who by day is 
the director of Packard Bell Financial Services. "What I did was combine all 
four (Beverly Hills elementary schools) into one Cub pack. That way we were 
able to draw support from the entire community." 
</P>
<P>
As word spread about the re-emergence of Cub Scouting in the city, Pack 100 
grew from six boys to 30 the next year, to 50 the next, and today boasts about 
100 Scouts, he said. 
</P>
<P>
For his work, Wright was recently named "Cubmaster of the Year" by the Scouts' 
Crescent Bay District, which includes most of the Cub packs in the Westside. 
</P>
<P>
"I think (Scouting) is extremely important in this day and age," said Wright, 
whose pack is involved in everything from food drives for the needy to planting 
trees in Maltz Park. "It gives the kids a sense of camaraderie . . . and it 
brings back a grass-roots involvement in the community that they don't get in 
any other activity." 
</P>
<P>
The Culver City Unified School District has named Laura Plasse as the new 
principal at Culver City High School. Plasse, the principal of Beaumont High 
School in Riverside County, will succeed Principal Glenn Cook, who will retire 
at the end of this school year. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Malcolm D. Cosgrove, a West Los Angeles physician, was reelected for a 
second one-year term as president of Sinai Temple. 
</P>
<P>
Also elected were six vice presidents: Judy Galperson, education; Dr. Paul 
Herman, ritual; Milton Hyman, membership; Jules Porter, community relations; 
Victor Sabah, finance, and Dorothy Salkin, administration. 
</P>
<P>
Basketball great Kareem Abdul-Jabbar received the UCLA Alumni Assn.'s highest 
honor, the Edward A. Dickson "Alumnus of the Year" award at the group's 45th 
Annual Alumni Awards for Excellence ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Jabbar, who retired last year after 20 years in the National Basketball 
Assn., led UCLA basketball teams to three national championships from 1966-69. 
</P>
<P>
Also honored at the ceremony was U.S. Rep. Edward R. Roybal (D-Los Angeles), 
who received an "Honorary Alumnus" award for his efforts to promote federal 
support of research programs and facilities at the university. 
</P>
<P>
The UCLA Alumni Assn. honored five UCLA graduates with Professional Achievement 
Awards. They are: Diane Freis, a fashion designer and founder of clothing 
manufacturer Diane Freis Enterprises; attorney Geraldine Hemmerling, the first 
woman president of the American College of Probate Counsel; Kenneth Karst, UCLA 
law professor; Army Gen. Louis Menetrey, commander-in-chief of the U.N. Command 
in South Korea, and James F. Montgomery, chairman and chief executive officer 
of Great Western Financial Corp. 
</P>
<P>
Loyola Marymount University has named Joseph G. Jabbra, academic and research 
vice president at St. Mary's University in Halifax, Nova Scotia, as its new 
academic vice president. He succeeds Albert Koppes, who, after a sabbatical, 
will return as professor of education. 
</P>
<P>
The university also announced the hiring of Gerald S. Jakubowski, interim dean 
of engineering at Memphis State University, as the new dean of the College of 
Science and Engineering. 
</P>
<P>
Ruth Grebler Sinaiko of Beverly Hills received the Eleanor Roosevelt Medallion 
from the American Friends of Tel Aviv University at its annual Benefactors' 
Ball at the Beverly Hills Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
The award was in recognition of Sinaiko's record of humanitarian service, which 
includes work with United Jewish Appeal, the Golda Meir Group of State of 
Israel Bonds and the Temple Israel Sisterhood. SHELDON ITO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Mark Wright, Cubmaster of the Year, initiated efforts to revive scouting 
in Beverly Hills. LISA ROMEREIN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
