<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOME ENTERTAINMENT: STEREO SYSTEMS WITH ELBOW ROOM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HARRY SOMERFIELD, Somerfield is a home entertainment columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
You've heard of "desktop publishing" -- well, now there's "desktop audio." The 
move to make modern electronics smaller and smaller has spilled over into the 
home entertainment arena. Tiny desktop audio components are becoming more and 
more popular, and are being produced by an ever-increasing variety of 
manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
As populations grow and land in urban areas becomes increasingly costly, we are 
all striving to make more efficient use of space. Whether you live in a studio 
apartment, a college dormitory, a town house or one of the latest generations 
of compact homes, you know that every inch of space is dear. "Desktop audio" 
components are designed and built to take advantage of this need to conserve 
space. 
</P>
<P>
Some manufacturers refer to the new generation of tiny audio components as 
"compact" rather than "desktop." The result is the same: several pieces of 
equipment occupy a very compact area. Desktop audio gear should not be confused 
with battery-powered portable equipment or "boom boxes." Desktop gear, though 
very small, is meant to live at home. 
</P>
<P>
While the size of the new audio equipment may have shrunk, the sound produced 
by it (as well as its price tag) can still be quite large. Here are three 
systems from different makers. Each is no larger than a foot-high pile of 
telephone books. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Casio Single Unit 
</P>
<P>
While the Casio MS-202 looks like a stack of four components, it's actually a 
single unit. It houses (from the top down) a turntable, an FM/AM tuner, an 
integrated amplifier with three-band graphic equalizer, and a dual-cassette 
deck. Also included are a wireless remote control and a pair of speakers. 
</P>
<P>
Though small, the system is not without bells and whistles. The full-size 
turntable is the belt-driven, semi-automatic type, and has a molded plastic 
dust cover. The tuner can be set to 12 FM and six AM stations. The cassette 
unit is capable of high-speed dubbing and can play two tapes consecutively. It 
can record from the turntable, the radio, or tape to tape. 
</P>
<P>
The MS-202 has an external input for attaching a compact disc player, 
television set, VCR or other audio source, and it has a headphone jack for 
private listening. The wireless remote controls on/off, volume, mute, and tuner 
scan. The Casio MS-202 is available now at a suggested retail price of $250. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Compact Magnavox 
</P>
<P>
The model AZ8700GY (where do they come up with these numbers?) from Magnavox is 
even more compact than the Casio, and while it lacks a turntable, it does 
feature a compact disc (CD) player. 
</P>
<P>
So, included in this desktop system are a CD player, FM/AM radio, an integrated 
amplifier with a four-band graphic equalizer, and a dual-cassette deck. A pair 
of speakers comes as part of the package. 
</P>
<P>
The CD player features repeat and shuffle play modes, as well as 20-track 
programmability. The FM/AM radio has electronic tuning, 12 station presets, and 
a built-in, telescoping antenna. The dual cassette deck offers high-speed 
dubbing and auto-reverse recording and playback. A pair of small, single-driver 
speakers is part of the system, and a headphone jack is included for private 
listening. 
</P>
<P>
The Magnavox AZ8700GY, a real mighty-mite of a system, will be available in 
September with a $320 price tag. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
High-End Yamaha 
</P>
<P>
I think the Yamaha YST-C11 is the best sounding of the three, but is three 
times the price of the others. The YST-C11 consists of a CD player, an FM/AM 
tuner, a dual-cassette tape recorder/player, an integrated stereo amplifier 
with four-band graphic equalizer, a wireless remote control and two speakers. 
</P>
<P>
The CD-player offers direct access, random play and full programmability. The 
FM/AM tuner allows direct entry of station frequencies, as well as 10 presets. 
The tape deck has auto-reverse playback on both cassettes, as well as Dolby B 
noise reduction. The speakers are of excellent quality, each with a 4.75-inch 
mid-range and 1-inch tweeter. The wireless remote contains 34 buttons, enough 
to control every function of the YST-C11. 
</P>
<P>
The system also includes a built-in timer, so you can be awakened (or lulled to 
sleep) by your favorite radio station, CD or tape -- or even record a radio 
program while you're away. The Yamaha YST-C11 desktop audio system sells for 
$999, and is available now. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
NEW COLUMN 
</P>
<P>
After shelter, food and transportation, home entertainment equipment is now the 
largest single item in the average consumer's budget. New technologies and new 
products are emerging constantly. Beginning this week, Home Entertainment, a 
column by syndicated writer Harry Somerfield, will guide consumers through the 
maze. The column will appear every two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
