<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROMANIAN STUDENTS CLEARED IN RIOTING; 
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST: THE INTERIOR MINISTER SAYS THE YOUTHS WERE NOT INVOLVED IN THE 
RECENT VIOLENCE. AUTHORITIES SEEM TO BE TRYING TO WIN OVER CRITICS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUCHAREST, Romania 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A government minister said Saturday that student groups were not to blame for 
the riots 10 days ago in Bucharest in which six people died. 
</P>
<P>
In a fresh indication that Romanian authorities are trying to win over their 
critics, Interior Minister Doru Ursu said: "It is more than clear that the 
students of Bucharest were in no way involved in the violent events of June 
13-15." 
</P>
<P>
University buildings were ransacked and students and other people were attacked 
by miners who came to the capital at the request of President Ion Iliescu to 
quell anti-government riots. 
</P>
<P>
Saturday night, a small crowd barricaded Bucharest's central boulevard on one 
side of University Square, a flash point of the recent violence, in a gesture 
of support for the arrested student leaders. 
</P>
<P>
Police persuaded the protesters to dismantle their barriers and allow traffic 
to pass after about 40 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Ion Ratiu, presidential candidate of the opposition National Peasants Party in 
the May elections, denied on television that his party had anything to do with 
last week's unrest. 
</P>
<P>
Ratiu, whose party offices and home were ransacked by the miners, said his 
party was not behind a seven-week demonstration that led to the violence. 
</P>
<P>
"I have never given one penny to the people in the square," he said in reply to 
allegations by the ruling National Salvation Front. 
</P>
<P>
"I have also worked by legal methods, never by such means as those used in 
University Square." 
</P>
<P>
Three delegates of the International Committee of the Red Cross are scheduled 
Monday to start visiting people arrested during the unrest to check on their 
health and conditions of detention. 
</P>
<P>
The ICRC representative in Romania, Thierry Meyrat, said the mission could last 
for months, depending on the timetable for any judicial proceedings against the 
detainees. He declined to answer questions about the number or whereabouts of 
prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
Ursu said he could not discuss individual students but added that "in no way 
can we talk about students' organizations participating in the events (last 
week's violence)." 
</P>
<P>
"I could even go further and say that the students through their calm attitude 
and their whole activity in that period have acted as a factor of 
stabilization." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Smiling miners from Barbatesti mine in Romania's Jiului valley are back 
at work a week after being summoned by government to crush opposition protest. 
Miners said they would do it again, if asked. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
